review_blob: Orange-colored ale.  Expresive aroma, but not oppressive.  Bitter swallow with a clean finish.  Like a weak Sam Adams.  Not memorable.

A glass of this gave me a stomach ache.  You could have just as easily called this Caramel Amber Ale, Caramel Lager, or Caramel anything and not known the difference.  This is the sort of beer that would appeal to the type of people who buy those artificially flavored 'hazelnut' coffees.  It's a shame to call this beer.

I rarely comment on head, but this one's fizzier than a can of warm Coke.  The flavor is decently roasted, but oppressive.  In short, this beer is pretentious as hell.   Avoid it unless you drive a luxury SUV.
Too similar to Sam Adam's Boston Lager in aroma, flavor, and appearance to justify the price difference.

Very enticing aroma.  Too malty to drink in large quantities.  Too heavy to accompany most meals.  Drink after dessert in place of a port wine.  The flavors are complex and stick around for a while.  This is better than Young's Dirty Dick's, Ram Rod and Waggledance.
Lager-like hoppy aroma (that is not a compliment) with a fine color of polished wood.  Smooth and slightly creamy, though underwhelming flavor and finish.

The pilsner-like aroma worried me, but the flavor is really decent.  Very easy to drink.  Leaves a bitter aftertaste like coffee does.  If I was a coffee drinker I think I'd like this beer much better.

I think a lot of the ratings below are a bit harsh on this beer.  It has a pleasant aroma and flavor (although admittedly they are  weak), similar to Harpoon's UFO but lacking its citrus lemon tartness.  However, this is what you'd expect from a hefeweiz.  I'd prefer it if it had a better mouthfeel, but, other than that, its an acceptable wheat beer.

Has an aroma of sweetened motor oil (which is a bad thing) and similar appearance (which is a good thing).  Flavors are very complex, but too 'peppy' for me.  No consistent theme: I taste coffee, dark berries, roasted wood, lots of malt, and I don't know what else.  I'd like this better if it was less complex and equally bitter, or less bitter and equally complex.

On some swallows, there is a coppery bitterness, on others, it tingles like touching a battery with your tongue.  The aroma and flavor almost make me think they poured in port wine.  Every swallow is different.  Very very rich and complex flavors.
Classic hoppy porter aroma and a bitter flavor.  This is a decent porter, but lacks a kick.
Sweet inviting aroma and pleasant color.  Overhopped and undercarbonated.  Not bad, but doesn't make a memorable impression either.
beer_name: Gritty McDuffs Lions Pride Brown Ale (Best Brown Ale)

review_blob:
Anyone who rates this stout less than a 4.0 is a drunken lunatic.  Previous reviews have complained about this brew's malty, burnt flavors and fizzy texture: these are among its best features.
It's not smooth, that's for certain, but its punch is part of its charm.

I was pleasantly surprised by this beer.  Wheat ales are not my favorite style, but I found this one very easy to drink.  Not at all bitter and very smooth.  Shipyard makes some decent beers - this one is not not expectional, but well worth trying.
Unique red color and hop-driven aroma.  Tastes like melted coffee ice cream with a very smooth swallow.  Tougher to drink the warmer it gets.

Mild but pleasing aroma and Coca-Cola-like color.  Flavor is slightly sickly and the body is too thin to make it an excellent stout, but complex malty flavors help to make up for some of its deficiencies.  Taste stays on the lips for a long time.

Pleasant aroma consisting primarily of hops, but certainly not overwhelming.  Color and opaqueness are very nice in their own right, but not what I expect from a porter.  I don't know why this is even called a porter. Malty flavor and easy to swallow.  I'd buy this again.

Hard to rate the aroma - there's very little to judge.  I don't know why I keep trying pilsners - I'm a porter or stout all the way.  A pleasantly mild citrus-like flavor in the taste, but very little body and a crisp, clean ending doesn't win it many points in my book.

A very aromatic brown with a beautiful color and nice creamy head.  Excellent flavor - smooth and malty - but the alcohol content adds too much of a tang to finish.  I don't understand aracauna's comments below -- the nose-tickle at the end ruins the experience.  If the brewers would cut back on the Scotch Ale factor, this would be an excellent brown.  As it is, it's not worth the price.

I tried this one 293 days after brewing (I didn't calculate that - I got it from timeanddate dot com), and I think it has suffered for the age.  Absolutely beautiful color and a very strong peanut buttery aroma.  Flavor is also peanut buttery with a strong maple sugar component, but the carbonation is a little flat.  Next time, I'll try this one in season.

Strong black spice aroma is the most appealing characteristic, and that's not saying much.  Unacceptably weak body and spice flavors dominate.  This beer's most redeeming feature is that I bought it on sale.

Easier to drink than higher alcohol chocolate stouts.  Aftertaste is much stronger than mid-swallow taste and is dominated by an artificial, candy-like flavor.  I want to be more impressed by this beer, but am not.

Mild aroma and lots of roasted flavors.  So easy to drink that, on the first drink, I didn't even notice I had swallowed.  A little too bitter for a porter-lover like me.  High alcohol content becomes much more noticable as temperature increases.

The aroma was so sweet and pleasant I had to stop halfway through pouring just to savor it.  The flavor though is sickly sweet, like alcoholic grape juice. I taste very little of the coffee/malt/chocolate flavors others have mentioned - only fruit and sugar.  Very smooth.  A good brew, but I expect Imperials to pack a little more punch.

Aroma very reminiscent of Guiness, though color is lighter.  Smokiness really brings out the flavors of smoked meat (pepperoni) and cheese (smoked mozarella).  Beer disappears from glass very quickly.

Simple aroma belies the complexity of the flavor.  Lots of roasted flavors early in swallow, with strongly alcoholic - almost vodka-like - finish.  I found it tough to finish the glass before it got warm.  Too strong for my preferences.

An Oprah Winfrey porter: thick, rich, smooth, and black. Like a Macanudo cigar without the smoky aftertaste.  A noticably bitter endtaste, but not at all unpleasant or intolerable.  A wonderful porter.

Aroma is mild and consists only of chicory; flavor is strong, but still one-note.  A very straightforward flavor; smooth and easy mouthfeel.  Personally, I don't care for the chicory flavor, but I recognize that this is a well-made beer.
UPDATED: OCT 31, 2003

Inviting aroma which gives the impression that the flavor will be sweet.  Heavy roasted flavors, though not all are pleasing.  The weakness of the flavor saves it from being overwhelming.  Oily finish.  Not an exceptional stout.

This is a great porter - a strong, inviting aroma; complex and constantly changing flavors during the taste; solid mouthfeel - but I'm not a coffee drinker.  I would have rated this beer higher if I was.
Coper color.  Malt aroma.  Sweet flavor.  Very smooth.  Good, but not extraordinary.  Would go well with starchy foods.
Looks like an ale, tastes like a lager.  This is not necessarily a good thing.
UPDATED: DEC 1, 2003
I found the flavor and mouthfeel to be weak and swallowing was not smooth.  I'll have to retry this one and rerate in the future.
Soft, mild aroma and a bitter flavor.  I only tried this one because its a Guinness product and I see no reason to try it again.

This beer is the perfect example of why I don't like pilsners.  Transparent; light in color; crisp flavor with a slightly rubbery aftertaste; and almost alcohol-free (only 4.4%).  Makes a good mouthwash.
This is an excellent porter - very smooth - but coffee aromas and flavors overwhelmed.  I'll have to give this one a second chance in the future.
Very little aroma, but beautiful color.  Easy to drink.  The flavor is hoppy, but not overwhelming.
Strong coffee aroma and coffee-like flavor, but without the bitterness.  Sweet for such a high-alcohol brew.  Very pleasing.

Black licorice dominates the aroma, building anticipation for tasting.  At least three flavors run a relay-race during the swallow: an initial candy sweetness, a strong hoppy middle, and a final and enduring roasted taste.  Not to be wasted on unsophisticates.
Floral aroma.  Very hoppy flavor.  Not as smooth as Samuel Smith's Tadcaster (Taddy) Porter, but an excellent porter nonetheless.

Roasted malt flavor lives up to its gorgeous amber color (though still lighter than I prefer).  Sweetness partially makes up for watery texture.  Otherwise, unimpressive, but better than I had expected.

Pumpkin orange color and bittery sweet flavor make this beer reminiscent of a highly hopped wild berry fruit ale.  Aroma is pleasant, though weak.  Hops dominate flavor during swallow, but malt flavor lingers if drinking straight - Try with a mild cheese or unsalted crackers.
